value.value: Bone Morphogenetic Protein Receptor Genes encode Bone Morphogenetic Protein Receptors, activated by Bone Morphogenetic Proteins, non-collagenous bone-growth regulatory factors synthesized as large precursor molecules that are cleaved by proteolytic enzymes and form an active homodimer or heterodimer of two related bone morphogenetic proteins that stimulate osteogenesis. (NCI)
This gene plays a role in the bone morphogenetic protein signaling pathway.
Bone morphogenetic protein receptor type-1A (532 aa, ~60 kDa) is encoded by the human BMPR1A gene. This protein is involved in ligand binding, signal transduction and embryonic development.
This gene is involved in receptor mediated ligand-induced signal transduction that is critical for endochondral bone formation and embryogenesis.
Bone morphogenetic protein receptor type-2 (1038 aa, ~115 kDa) is encoded by the human BMPR2 gene. This protein plays a role in signaling and embryonic pattern formation.

Any substance that inhibits glutathione transferase, an enzyme that catalyzes the addition of a glutathione moiety to a substrate and is involved in detoxification of endogenous and exogenous compounds. Inhibition of glutathione transferase can increase the half-life and activity of chemotherapeutic agents.
This gene plays a role in development. It is also involved in both cell growth and differentiation.
This gene is involved in the mediation of cytotoxic T cells and class I major histocompatibility interactions.
Cytoplasmic tyrosine-protein kinase BMX (675 aa, ~78 kDa) is encoded by the human BMX gene. This protein is involved in protein phosphorylation, signaling, cell adhesion and apoptosis.
This gene is involved in the regulation of apoptosis and induces cell death.
BCL2/adenovirus E1B 19 kDa protein-interacting protein 3-like (219 aa, ~24 kDa) is encoded by the human BNIP3L gene. This protein is involved in the induction of apoptosis.
This gene plays a role in signal transduction and regulation of transcription. It is involved in brain development and spermatogenesis.
Bromodomain-containing protein 2 (801 aa, ~88 kDa) is encoded by the human BRD2 gene. This protein plays a role in spermatogenesis.
This gene is involved in signal transduction and protein trafficking. It also plays a role in the immune response.
Signal-transducing adaptor protein 1 (295 aa, ~34 kDa) is encoded by the human STAP1 gene. This protein is involved in promoting the activity of tyrosine-protein kinase Tec.
This gene is involved in the regulation of the G1/S transition of the cell cycle.
For non-invasive detection, Protease-Activated Near-Infrared Fluorescent Probes are used for in vivo Imaging of tumors in Mice.
Protein BTG2 (158 aa, ~17 kDa) is encoded by the human BTG2 gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of both cell proliferation and transcription.
This gene plays a role in the regulation of beta-adrenergic receptor-mediated signaling.
Beta-adrenergic receptor kinase 1 (689 aa, ~80 kDa) is encoded by the human GRK2 gene. This protein is involved in both G protein-coupled receptor signaling and muscle contraction.
This gene is involved in the regulation of signaling by beta-adrenergic and related G protein-coupled receptors.
Beta-adrenergic receptor kinase 2 (688 aa, ~80 kDa) is encoded by the human GRK3 gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of beta-adrenergic receptor-mediated signaling.
This gene plays a regulatory role in transcription and is involved in male germ cell differentiation.
AF4/FMR2 family member 4 (1163 aa, ~127 kDa) is encoded by the human AFF4 gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of transcription.
This gene plays a role in the regulation of the central nervous system and cardiovascular functions that are mediated by angiotensin.
Type-2 angiotensin II receptor (363 aa, ~41 kDa) is encoded by the human AGTR2 gene. This protein is involved in signal transduction, apoptosis, and the regulation of blood pressure.
This gene plays a role in tumor suppression.
Substances that stimulate the immune system.
Beta/gamma crystallin domain-containing protein 1 (1723 aa, ~189 kDa) is encoded by the human CRYBG1 gene. This protein plays a role in protein-protein interactions.
This gene plays a role in cellular proliferation and may be involved in tumor reversion.
Interferon-inducible protein AIM2 (343 aa, ~39 kDa) is encoded by the human AIM2 gene. This protein may be involved in apoptosis, inflammation and tumor suppression.
This gene is involved in transcription of ribosomal RNA which plays a role in protein synthesis.
This gene is involved in RNA binding and protein translation.
60S ribosomal protein L8 (257 aa, ~28 kDa) is encoded by the human RPL8 gene. This protein is involved in protein translation.
This gene plays a role in RNA binding and protein translation.
60S ribosomal protein L19 (196 aa, ~23 kDa) is encoded by the human RPL10 gene. This protein is involved in assembly and function of the large ribosomal subunit.
This gene is involved in RNA binding and protein synthesis.
60S ribosomal protein L29 (159 aa, ~18 kDa) is encoded by the human RPL29 gene. This protein plays a role in ribosomal structure and heparan sulfate binding.

A family of globular proteins found in many plant and animal tissues that tend to bind a wide variety of ligands.  Albumin is the main protein in blood plasma.  Low serum levels occur in conditions associated with malnutrition, inflammation and liver and kidney diseases.
An agent that enhances the activity or therapeutic effect of another pharmacologic substance without having much, if any, therapeutic impact by itself.
This gene plays a role in the repression of both transcription and cell proliferation.
C-terminal-binding protein 1 (440 aa, ~48 kDa) is encoded by the human CTBP1 gene. This protein is involved in oxidation and the negative regulation of both cell proliferation and transcription.
This gene is involved in DNA repair and meiotic recombination.
MutS protein homolog 4 (936 aa, ~105 kDa) is encoded by the human MSH4 gene. This protein plays a role in reciprocal recombination and proper segregation of homologous chromosomes at meiosis.
This gene plays a role in meiotic recombination and centromere association.
This gene is involved in the regulation of blood vessel growth. It also plays a role as a neurotrophic factor for motor neurons.
Meiotic recombination protein SPO11 (396 aa, ~45 kDa) is encoded by the human SPO11 gene. This protein is involved in the modulation of chromosomal recombination.
Adjuvant used in chemotherapy that acts by stimulating the immune system.
This gene plays a role in vasculogenesis.
This gene is involved in neuroendocrine mediation and anti-inflammatory immune responses.
